<DOC><DOCNO> AP880613-0145 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1556EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-ChildCarePoll     06-13 0215</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Child Care Poll,200</SECOND><HEAD>Most Voters Polled Favor $2.5 Billion Expansion of Child Care</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three out of five voters favor a massive $2.5billion expansion of federal aid for child care, according to apoll released Monday by two leading proponents of the legislation.   Of the 901 voters sampled in the nationwide telephone survey, 60percent said they favored the Act for Better Child Care proposal ofRep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich., and Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., and32 percent said they opposed it.   The survey by Marttila andamp; Kiley Inc. of Boston was conducted fromMay 31 through June 5 and carried a margin of error of 3.2percentage points.   The poll was commissioned by the Children's Defense Fund and theAmerican Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, twoof the leading lobbying forces behind the Dodd-Kildee bill.   Three-fourths of the money in the legislation would provide newchild care subsidies to families making up to 115 percent of astate's median income. Federal aid for child care through taxcredits and grants currently totals some $6.9 billion a year.   Business groups and the Reagan administration oppose theDodd-Kildee bill and have united behind a smaller $375 millioncounterproposal authored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Rep.Nancy Johnson, R-Conn.</TEXT></DOC>